Lab Environment Setup
Important Note: Al Nafi provides ready-to-use Linux-based cloud machines. Simply click Start Lab to begin - no need to build your own virtual machine. All tasks in this lab will be performed on a single Linux machine using containerization and virtualization technologies.

Task 1: Configure pfSense as a Firewall
Subtask 1.1: Install Required Virtualization Tools
First, we need to install the necessary tools to run pfSense in a virtualized environment on our Linux machine.

# Update the system packages
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install QEMU/KVM virtualization tools
sudo apt install -y qemu-kvm libvirt-daemon-system libvirt-clients bridge-utils virt-manager

# Install additional networking tools
sudo apt install -y openvswitch-switch openvswitch-common

# Add current user to libvirt group
sudo usermod -a -G libvirt $USER

# Start and enable libvirt service
sudo systemctl start libvirtd
sudo systemctl enable libvirtd
Subtask 1.2: Download pfSense ISO
Download the pfSense Community Edition ISO file:

# Create directory for ISO files
mkdir -p ~/lab-isos
cd ~/lab-isos

# Download pfSense CE ISO (latest stable version)
wget https://frafiles.netgate.com/mirror/downloads/pfSense-CE-2.7.2-RELEASE-amd64.iso.gz

# Extract the ISO file
gunzip pfSense-CE-2.7.2-RELEASE-amd64.iso.gz
Subtask 1.3: Create pfSense Virtual Machine
Create a virtual machine for pfSense using command line tools:

# Create disk image for pfSense
qemu-img create -f qcow2 ~/lab-isos/pfsense.qcow2 20G

# Create pfSense VM with specific network configuration
virt-install \
  --name pfsense \
  --ram 2048 \
  --disk path=~/lab-isos/pfsense.qcow2,size=20 \
  --vcpus 2 \
  --os-type linux \
  --os-variant freebsd12.0 \
  --network bridge=virbr0 \
  --network bridge=virbr0 \
  --graphics vnc,listen=0.0.0.0 \
  --console pty,target_type=serial \
  --cdrom ~/lab-isos/pfSense-CE-2.7.2-RELEASE-amd64.iso \
  --boot cdrom
Subtask 1.4: Install and Configure pfSense
Access the pfSense VM console:

# Connect to pfSense VM console
virsh console pfsense
Installation Steps:

When pfSense boots, select Install pfSense
Choose Auto (UFS) for disk partitioning
Wait for installation to complete
Remove installation media and reboot
Accept default interface assignments (WAN: em0, LAN: em1)
Initial Configuration:

# After pfSense boots, configure interfaces
# At pfSense console menu, select option 2 (Set interface(s) IP address)

# Configure LAN interface:
# - Select LAN interface (2)
# - Set IP address: 192.168.100.1
# - Set subnet mask: 24
# - Press Enter for no upstream gateway
# - Press Enter for no IPv6
# - Enable DHCP server: y
# - DHCP range start: 192.168.100.10
# - DHCP range end: 192.168.100.50
# - Revert to HTTP for webConfigurator: y
