Task 2: Set up Kali Linux for Testing
Subtask 2.1: Install Kali Linux Tools on Host System
Instead of creating another VM, we'll install Kali Linux tools directly on our host system:

# Add Kali Linux repository
echo "deb http://http.kali.org/kali kali-rolling main non-free contrib" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kali.list

# Add Kali Linux GPG key
wget -q -O - https://archive.kali.org/archive-key.asc | sudo apt-key add -

# Update package lists
sudo apt update

# Install essential Kali Linux tools
sudo apt install -y kali-linux-core kali-tools-top10

# Install additional penetration testing tools
sudo apt install -y nmap nikto sqlmap dirb gobuster hydra john hashcat
Subtask 2.2: Configure Network Interface for Testing
Create a virtual network interface for testing:

# Create virtual network interface script
cat > ~/setup-test-interface.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

# Create virtual network interface
sudo ip link add name veth-test type veth peer name veth-test-peer

# Configure IP addresses
sudo ip addr add 192.168.100.100/24 dev veth-test
sudo ip addr add 192.168.100.101/24 dev veth-test-peer

# Bring interfaces up
sudo ip link set veth-test up
sudo ip link set veth-test-peer up

# Add route to pfSense network
sudo ip route add 192.168.100.0/24 dev veth-test

echo "Virtual test interface configured successfully"
echo "Test interface IP: 192.168.100.100"
echo "Peer interface IP: 192.168.100.101"
EOF

chmod +x ~/setup-test-interface.sh
./setup-test-interface.sh
Subtask 2.3: Create Kali Linux Testing Environment
Set up a dedicated directory structure for penetration testing:

# Create penetration testing directory structure
mkdir -p ~/pentest-lab/{scripts,results,targets,tools}

# Create target discovery script
cat > ~/pentest-lab/scripts/discover-targets.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Network Discovery Script ==="
echo "Scanning local network for active hosts..."

# Discover active hosts on the network
nmap -sn 192.168.100.0/24 | tee ~/pentest-lab/results/host-discovery.txt

echo ""
echo "=== Port Scanning ==="
echo "Scanning pfSense firewall..."

# Scan pfSense firewall
nmap -sS -O 192.168.100.1 | tee ~/pentest-lab/results/pfsense-scan.txt

echo ""
echo "Results saved to ~/pentest-lab/results/"
EOF

chmod +x ~/pentest-lab/scripts/discover-targets.sh
